VALUES
(44, 11, 1, 38, 8, 20, 23, 'Gentiles had also received the word of God', 'Gentiles Seeking the Lord', 'This connection highlights the theme of Gentiles receiving the word of God and seeking the Lord. Both passages emphasize the inclusion of nations and peoples in worship and prayer before God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 1, 44, 14, 27, 27, 'Gentiles had also received the word of God', 'Gentiles Receiving the Word', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of Gentiles in the faith. Acts 11:1 mentions the Gentiles receiving the word of God, while Acts 14:27 highlights how God opened the door of faith unto the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 2, 44, 10, 45, 45, 'they that were of the circumcision', 'Astonishment of the Circumcision', 'Both passages emphasize the reaction of those ''of the circumcision'' to the inclusion of Gentiles in the faith. The astonishment in Acts 10:45 sets the stage for the contention mentioned in Acts 11:2, highlighting a significant moment of conflict within the early church.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 2, 44, 10, 9, 9, NULL, 'Peter''s Journey to Prayer', 'This connection highlights Peter''s actions as he transitions from prayer to facing opposition. Both passages emphasize Peter''s role in significant events that shape the early church.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 2, 44, 15, 1, 1, 'they that were of the circumcision', 'Circumcision and Salvation Debate', 'This connection highlights the contention regarding circumcision as a requirement for salvation. Both passages emphasize the conflict between those advocating for circumcision and the early Christian community''s understanding of salvation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 2, 44, 21, 20, 23, 'they that were of the circumcision contended with him', 'Controversy Over Jewish Customs', 'This connection highlights the ongoing contention regarding Jewish customs and the law. Both passages emphasize the conflict between Jewish believers and the teachings of Peter and Paul about circumcision and adherence to the law.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 2, 48, 2, 12, 14, 'they that were of the circumcision', 'Peter''s Withdrawal from Gentiles', 'This connection highlights Peter''s actions regarding the Gentiles, as seen in both passages. In Acts, Peter faces contention from those of the circumcision, while in Galatians, he withdraws from eating with Gentiles due to fear of them.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 44, 10, 28, 28, 'men uncircumcised, and didst eat with them', 'Connection of Jewish Law and Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the issue of Jews interacting with Gentiles. Acts 11:3 references eating with uncircumcised men, while Acts 10:28 discusses the unlawfulness of such associations, highlighting a significant shift in understanding regarding purity laws.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 48, 2, 12, 12, 'didst eat with them', 'Eating with Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the act of eating with Gentiles, highlighting the tension between Jewish and Gentile believers. The SOURCE verse points to the criticism of Peter for associating with uncircumcised men, while the TARGET passage describes Peter''s withdrawal from eating with Gentiles due to fear of those from the circumcision party.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 42, 15, 2, 2, 'didst eat with them', 'Eating with Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize the act of eating with those considered unclean or sinful. In Acts, Peter is criticized for eating with uncircumcised men, while in Luke, Jesus is criticized for receiving sinners and eating with them.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 44, 10, 48, 48, 'men uncircumcised', 'Baptism and Acceptance of Gentiles', 'This connection highlights the acceptance of Gentiles in the early church. In Acts 11:3, the concern about eating with uncircumcised men relates to the baptism of those Gentiles in Acts 10:48.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 46, 5, 11, 11, 'didst eat with them', 'Eating with Uncircumcised Men', 'This connection highlights the theme of association with those considered unclean or sinful. Both passages emphasize the implications of eating with individuals who do not adhere to certain moral or religious standards.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 63, 1, 10, 10, NULL, 'Caution Against Unacceptable Associations', 'This connection highlights the concern over associating with those who do not adhere to proper doctrine. Both passages emphasize the importance of maintaining purity in fellowship and teaching.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 4, 42, 1, 3, 3, NULL, 'Orderly Presentation of Events', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of presenting information in a systematic manner. Peter ''expounded it by order'' in Acts, while Luke states he aims to write ''in order'' for Theophilus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 4, 6, 22, 21, 31, NULL, 'Witness and Rehearsal of Events', 'This connection highlights the theme of recounting significant events for the sake of future generations. Both passages emphasize the importance of clear communication and understanding among the people of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 4, 20, 15, 1, 1, NULL, 'Communication and Conflict Resolution', 'This connection highlights the importance of how words can influence reactions. Peter''s careful explanation in Acts reflects the idea that a soft answer can mitigate conflict, as noted in Proverbs.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 4, 44, 14, 27, 27, NULL, 'Rehearsing God''s Works', 'This connection highlights the act of rehearsing events related to God''s work among the Gentiles. Both passages emphasize the importance of recounting what God has done, showcasing the growth of the early church.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 44, 10, 9, 32, 'a certain vessel descend, as it had been a great sheet, let down from heaven by four corners', 'Vision of the Vessel', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s vision of a vessel descending from heaven, which signifies a divine message regarding clean and unclean animals. This vision serves as a pivotal moment leading to Peter''s encounter with Cornelius, illustrating the breaking of Jewish dietary laws and the inclusion of Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 24, 1, 11, 14, NULL, 'Divine Communication in Visions', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine communication through visions. Both passages depict God revealing significant messages to His servants, with Peter in a trance and Jeremiah receiving visions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 26, 2, 9, 9, 'a certain vessel descend', 'Divine Communication in Visions', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine communication through visions. Both passages describe a significant revelation involving a vessel or roll sent from heaven, indicating God''s message to the recipient.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 30, 7, 4, 7, NULL, 'Divine Visions and Revelations', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine visions, as both passages describe God revealing significant messages to the prophets. In Acts, Peter experiences a vision in a trance, while Amos receives a vision from the Lord regarding judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 30, 8, 2, 2, NULL, 'Divine Revelation and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine revelation through visions, as seen in both passages. In Acts, Peter receives a vision that signifies a new understanding, while in Amos, the vision of summer fruit symbolizes impending judgment on Israel.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 44, 9, 10, 10, NULL, 'Visions in Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of receiving a vision while in prayer. This connection highlights the significance of divine communication through visions in moments of spiritual focus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 47, 12, 1, 3, NULL, 'Visions and Revelations Connection', 'Both passages emphasize experiences of visions and revelations from God. Acts describes a vision received during prayer, while 2 Corinthians discusses a man who experienced a profound revelation, highlighting the theme of divine communication.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 6, 42, 4, 20, 20, 'fastened mine eyes', 'Focus on the Eyes', 'This connection highlights the theme of attention and observation. In both passages, the act of fastening one''s eyes signifies a moment of significant focus and contemplation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 6, 44, 3, 4, 4, 'fastened mine eyes', 'Connection of Focused Attention', 'Both passages emphasize the act of ''fastening'' one''s eyes, indicating a deliberate focus on what is before them. This connection highlights the importance of attention in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 45, 14, 14, 14, 'nothing common or unclean', 'Clean and Unclean Concepts', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of what is considered clean or unclean. Acts 11:8 reflects Peter''s struggle with dietary laws, while Romans 14:14 asserts that nothing is unclean of itself, highlighting a shift in understanding regarding purity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 28, 9, 3, 3, 'nothing common or unclean', 'Connection of Clean and Unclean', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of unclean things. In Acts, Peter refuses to eat anything unclean, while Hosea describes Ephraim eating unclean things in Assyria.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 46, 7, 14, 14, 'nothing common or unclean', 'Holiness and Cleansing Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of what is considered clean and unclean. In Acts 11:8, Peter refers to things that are unclean, while 1 Corinthians 7:14 discusses the sanctification of the unbelieving spouse and children, indicating a shift in their status from unclean to holy.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 3, 10, 10, 10, 'nothing common or unclean hath at any time entered into my mouth', 'Clean and Unclean Distinction', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between clean and unclean. Acts 11:8 reflects Peter''s adherence to dietary laws outlined in Leviticus 10:10, which instructs the faithful to differentiate between holy and unholy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
